@endnode

@node Features

DoIcon is yet another icon tool, but it's designed for quick shell-usage
and can perfectly work together with DirOpus or any similar tool.
DoIcon is @{i}pure@{ui} and can be made @{i}resident@{ui}.


@{u}Features:@{uu}

      · Displaying of icon related values...
        type, defaulttool, stacksize, highlightmethod, position, dimensions,
        tooltypes, drawervalues and number of bit-planes

      · Manipulation of the above listed values...

      · Manipulation of the drawer showmode
        (show all files/only files with icon).

      · Manipulation of the drawer viewmode
        (listed as icon, by name, date or size).
 
      · Copying of stacksize, type, position, defaulttool and icon image
        into an other icon

      · Search & replace of a specified defaulttool (with pattern-support)

      · Manipulation of tooltypes (add, change, toggle, delete, clear all)

      · Search & replace of specified tooltypes (with pattern-support)

      · Search & delete of a specified tooltype (with pattern-support)

      · Search & copying of a specified tooltype to a destination icon
        (with pattern-support)

      · Search & updating of a specified tooltype to a destination icon
        (Tooltype is only copied if it is not already in the destination icon.)
        (with pattern-support)

      · Copying of a specific or all tooltypes into an other icon

      · Sorting of tooltype array

 @{b}NEW!@{ub} · Stripping of 'NewIcon' tooltypes

      · Updating of tooltypes (automatic copying of new tooltypes
        from a source into a destination icon

      · Checking of tooltype-values for specified tooltypes
   
      · Strip number of bit-planes.

      · Converting icons to 8 bit-planes
        (For icons which are not displayed correctly on >8 color WBs)

      · Remapping icon colors (1.x style <-> 2.x/3.x style)
 
      · Remapping icon colors (MagicWB 8 color -> Standard 4 color)
        (Two different remap-methods are available, for best look of
         MagicWB icons on a 4 color Workbench)

      · Swapping icon images (normal/select)

      · Deleting icons (with Workbench refresh)

      · Calling of Workbench information-requester from Shell

      · Converting icon-ImageData to C-Sourcecode

      · All above mentioned functions can be used together with a file pattern
        (with optional recursive directory scanning)

      · Recursively deleting of the old 1.x ".info"-drawerfiles

      · Full locale support, you can use DoIcon in your preferred language
        (Currently available languages are English, German, French, Danish
         Finish and Polish.)

@endnode

@node Requirements

@{u}DoIcon needs:@{uu}

   · any Amiga :-)

   · Workbench 2.04 or higher

   · some bytes of memory during usage... ;)

   · and of course, lots of icons... :-)

   · and it must be run from shell, if you try to run it from Workbench
     it will just exit


@endnode

@node Installation

@{u}Installation is very easy:@{uu}

@{b}If you want to use the Installer, simply double-click on "Install-DoIcon"!@{ub}


If you want to install DoIcon by hand, just do the following:

 1) Copy "DoIcon" in any directory you want.
    I recommend a directory whithin your search path (eg. C:)

 2) When a catalog for your preferred language is available, just copy 
    the appropriate DoIcon.catalog to "Locale:Catalogs/<language>".

 3) This documentation may copied to the directory,
    where you store your guide files.


 @{i}just do it!@{ui}

@endnode

@node Usage

@{u}Usage:@{uu} DoIcon <@{" FROM/A/M " Link File}> [<@{" TO/K " Link DestinationFile}>] [<options>]


@{u}Options:@{uu}       @{" Type=T                     " Link Type}   (switch)
               @{" newType=newT               " Link newType}   (string-option)
               @{" copyType=copyT             " Link copyType}   (switch)

               @{" Position=XY                " Link Position}   (switch)
               @{" copyPosition=copyXY        " Link copyPosition}   (switch)
               @{" newX  / newY               " Link newpos}   (number-option)
               @{" freeX / freeY              " Link free}   (switch)
               @{" newDX / newDY              " Link newdpos}   (number-option)
               @{" newDWidth / newDHeight     " Link newddim}   (number-option)
               @{" drawerShow=dShow           " Link drawershow}   (string-option)
               @{" drawerView=dView           " Link drawerview}   (string-option)
               @{" copyDrawerPosition=copyDXY " Link copyDrawerPosition}   (switch) 

               @{" Stacksize=SS               " Link Stacksize}   (switch)
               @{" newStacksize=newSS         " Link newStacksize}   (number-option)
               @{" copyStacksize=copySS       " Link copyStacksize}   (switch)

               @{" Defaulttool=DT             " Link Defaulttool}   (switch)
               @{" newDefaulttool=newDT       " Link newDefaulttool}   (string-option)
               @{" copyDefaulttool=copyDT     " Link copyDefaulttool}   (switch)
               @{" searchDefaulttool=searchDT " Link searchDefaulttool}   (string-option)

               @{" Depth=D                    " Link Depth}   (switch)
               @{" stripDepth=stripD          " Link StripDepth}   (number-option)
               @{" DepthTo8                   " Link DepthTo8}   (switch)
               @{" Remap                      " Link Remap}   (switch)
               @{" RemapMWB                   " Link RemapMWB}   (number-option)
               @{" Highlight=HL               " Link Highlight}   (switch)
               @{" newHighlight=newHL         " Link newHighlight}   (string-option)
               @{" swapImage=sIMG             " Link swapImage}   (switch)
               @{" copyImage=copyIMG          " Link copyImage}   (switch)

               @{" Tooltypes=TT               " Link Tooltypes}   (switch)
               @{" changeTooltype=cTT         " Link changeTooltype}   (string/number-option)
               @{" addTooltype=aTT            " Link addTooltype}   (string-option)
               @{" copyTooltype=copyTT        " Link copyTooltypes}   (number-option)
               @{" updateTooltypes=upTT       " Link updateTooltypes}   (switch)
               @{" toggleTooltype=tTT         " Link toggleTooltype}   (number-option)
               @{" deleteTooltype=delTT       " Link deleteTooltype}   (number-option)
               @{" clearTooltypes=clearTT     " Link clearTooltypes}   (switch)
               @{" sortTooltypes=sortTT       " Link sortTooltypes}   (switch)
               @{" searchTooltype=searchTT    " Link searchTooltypes}   (string-option)
               @{" checkTooltypeValue=cTTV    " Link checkTooltypeValue}   (string-option)

     @{b}NEW!@{ub}      @{" stripNewIcon=stripNI       " Link stripnewicon}   (switch)

               @{" WBInfo=GUI                 " Link WBInfo}   (switch)
               @{" ImageToSource=IMGtoSRC     " Link ImageToSource}   (switch)
               @{" Delete                     " Link Delete}   (switch)
               @{" KillOldInfo                " Link KillOldInfo}   (switch)

               @{" Deep=All                   " Link Deep}   (switch)
               @{" Quiet                      " Link Quiet}   (switch)


If you supply no options, DoIcon will display all icon values, 
depending on the icon-type.

@endnode

@node File
@prev Usage

FROM

DoIcon needs this argument for any operation.

You can supply the suffix ".info" to the filename, but you need not.

Since version 1.1 you can supply standard AmigaDOS-patterns (wildcards) as
a file-argument.
All specified operations are used on the matching icons.
If you use the @{"Deep/All" Link Deep} switch together with a pattern,
all sub-directories are entered and checked for matching icons.

Since version 1.2 you can supply multiple files/patterns as a file-argument.

Since version 1.4 you can give a destination icon via the @{" TO " Link DestinationFile} option
for some operations.

If you use the @{"KillOldInfo" Link KillOldInfo}-option you need to supply a device-
or directory-name where DoIcon should start with the search.


@{u}Examples:@{uu} "DoIcon sys:disk" will show you some information about this disk-icon.

          "DoIcon sys:disk.info" will do the same.

          "DoIcon sys:wbstartup/#? checktooltypevalue=cx_popkey"
           This will output the values of the CX_PopKey-tooltype of the icons.

          "DoIcon sys:#? delete deep" will delete all icons...
           (This is just an example, DON'T really try this... ;-)

          "DoIcon icon1 icon2 icon3" will show some info about these icons.

          "DoIcon dir1/#? dir2/#?" will show info about all icons in these dirs.

          "DoIcon sys: @{"KillOldInfo" Link KillOldInfo}" will delete all ".info"-files
           on your system-device.


@endnode

@node DestinationFile
@prev Usage

TO


You can supply the suffix ".info" to the filename, but you need not.

If you give a destination icon via TO you can only have @{u}one@{uu} source icon.
File patterns are not possible rsp. allowed. The @{"Deep/All" Link Deep} has no
effect when a destination icon is given.


Options that can be used with a destination icon are @{"copyType" Link copyType}, @{"copyPosition" Link copyPosition},
@{"copyDrawerPosition" Link copyDrawerPosition}, @{"copyStacksize" Link copyStacksize}, @{"copyDefaulttool" Link copyDefaulttool}, @{"copyImage" Link copyImage},
@{"copyTooltypes" Link copyTooltypes} and @{"updateTooltypes" Link updateTooltypes}.


@{u}Examples:@{uu} "DoIcon sys:disk to work:disk copyImage"
           This copies the icon image.

          "DoIcon icon1 to icon2 copyTooltypes"
           This copies all tooltypes from icon1.info to icon2.info.

@endnode

@node Type
@prev Usage

TYPE

minimum acceptable abbreviation: "T"

This switch shows you the icon-type of the supplied iconfile.
This can be DISK, DRAWER, TOOL, PROJECT, TRASHCAN, DEVICE, KICK or APPICON.
(eh... but DEVICE, KICK and APPICON may not appear very often... ;-))


@{u}Example:@{uu} "DoIcon sys:disk type" will return DISK as icon-type

@endnode

@node newType
@prev Usage

NEWTYPE

minimum acceptable abbreviation: "newT"

This option changes the icon-type.
It needs on of the following strings as input:
DISK, DRAWER, TOOL, PROJECT, TRASHCAN, DEVICE, KICK or APPICON.
(DEVICE, KICK and APPICON may not used normaly...)

Dependand on the supplied icon and the new icon-type default values
like stacksize, window-position, window-dimensions... are set
automatically during conversion.
If you convert an icon to DISK or DRAWER DoIcon tries to use the window-
position and dimensions from "ENV:SYS/def_disk.info" rsp. 
"ENV:SYS/def_drawer.info". 
If DoIcon don't find this icon, system defaults are used.


@{u}Example:@{uu} "DoIcon sys:disk newtype=trashcan" will transform your disk-icon
          into a trashcan-icon. (just an example, don't try it... ;-)

@endnode

@node copyType
@prev Usage

COPYTYPE

minimum acceptable abbreviation: "copyT"

This option can only be used together with the @{" TO-Option " Link DestinationFile}!

The value of the icon type is copied from a source to a destination icon.

@{u}Example:@{uu} "DoIcon source_icon to dest_icon copyt"
          'dest_icon' get the same type as 'source_icon'.

@endnode

@node Position
@prev Usage

POSITION

minimum acceptable abbreviation: "XY"

This switch shows you the icon-position (relative to the window it's in)
and the icon-dimensions in pixels.
If you have supplied a DISK or DRAWER icon the window-position and
window-dimensions are automatically displayed.


@{u}Example:@{uu} "DoIcon sys:disk xy" (just try it)

@endnode

@node copyPosition
@prev Usage

COPYPOSITION

minimum acceptable abbreviation: "COPYXY"

This option can only be used together with the @{" TO-Option " Link DestinationFile}!

The icon position is copied from the source to the destination icon.


@{u}Example:@{uu} "DoIcon source_icon to dest_icon copyxy"

@endnode

@node newpos "NewPosition"
@prev Usage

NEWX / NEWY

With newX and newY you can change the position of the icon.
NewX stands for the left edge of the icon and newY for the top edge.


@{u}Example:@{uu} "DoIcon sys:disk newx=100 newy=100"
         This will move your disk-icon to an other position...

@endnode

@node free "UnSnapshot"
@prev Usage

FREEX / FREEY

With the freeX and freeY switch you can free the icon-position.
In other words, you can unsnapshot the icon with these switches.


@{u}Example:@{uu} "DoIcon sys:disk freex freey" will unsnapshot your disk-icon


@{u}Restrictions:@{uu} It's possible to free the x- and y-position separately.
              With freeY everything goes fine, but when only the x-position is
              freed the Workbench even behaves like both positions are free!
              When the Workbench finds a free x-position it concludes that
              the y-position must be free too...  :-(


@endnode

@node newdpos "NewDrawerPosition"
@prev Usage

NEWDX / NEWDY

With newDX and newDY you can change the window-position of the icon.
NewDX stands for the left edge of the drawer-window and newDY for 
the top edge.
The supplied icon should be of type DISK or DRAWER.


@{u}Example:@{uu} "DoIcon sys:disk newdx=100 newdy=100"
         This will change the position of your system-window.


@{u}Restrictions:@{uu} The window-position (if it's open) is not refreshed
              automatically. If you want the changes to take effect,
              you should "update" the window with the icon
              (NOT the window you have changed!).

@endnode

@node newddim "NewDrawerDimensions"
@prev Usage

NEWDWIDTH / NEWDHEIGHT

With newDWidth and newDHeight you can change the window-dimensions 
of the icon.
The supplied icon should be of type DISK or DRAWER.


@{u}Example:@{uu} "DoIcon sys:disk newdwidth=200 newdheight=200"
         This will change the dimensions of your system-window.


@{u}Restrictions:@{uu} The window-dimensions (if it's open) are not refreshed
              automatically. If you want the changes to take effect,
              you should "update" the window with the icon
              (NOT the window you have changed!).

@endnode

@node DrawerShow
@prev Usage

DRAWERSHOW

minimum acceptable abbreviation: "DSHOW"

This option changes the showmode of the drawer window.
This means, if only files with an icon are displayed in the window or
all files are displayed.
As argument you give either "ICON" or "ALL".

@{u}Example:@{uu} "DoIcon drawericon dshow=all"
         This will change the drawer window to display all files.


@{u}Restrictions:@{uu} The window showmode (if it's open) is not refreshed
              automatically. If you want the changes to take effect,
              you should "update" the window with the icon
              (NOT the window you have changed!).

@endnode

@node DrawerView
@prev Usage

DRAWERVIEW

minimum acceptable abbreviation: "DVIEW"

This option changes the viewmode of the drawer window.
This means, if the files in the window are listed as icons, by name, date
or size.
As argument you give either "ICON", "NAME", "DATE" or "SIZE".

@{u}Example:@{uu} "DoIcon drawericon dview=name"
         This will change the drawer window to list the contents by name.


@{u}Restrictions:@{uu} The window viewmode (if it's open) is not refreshed
              automatically. If you want the changes to take effect,
              you should "update" the window with the icon
              (NOT the window you have changed!).

@endnode

@node copyDrawerPosition
@prev Usage

COPYDRAWERPOSITION

minimum acceptable abbreviation: "COPYDXY"

This option can only be used together with the @{" TO-Option " Link DestinationFile}!


@{u}Example:@{uu} "DoIcon source_drawer to dest_drawer copydxy"


@{u}Restrictions:@{uu} The window-dimensions (if it's open) are not refreshed
              automatically. If you want the changes to take effect,
              you should "update" the window with the destination icon
              (NOT the window you have changed!).

@endnode

@node Stacksize
@prev Usage

STACKSIZE

minimum acceptable abbreviation: "SS"

This switch displays the Stacksize of the supplied icon.
The icon should be of type TOOL or PROJECT.


@{u}Example:@{uu} "DoIcon sys:yourtool ss" (easy, isn't it? :-)

@endnode

@node newStacksize
@prev Usage

NEWSTACKSIZE

minimum acceptable abbreviation: "NEWSS"

This option changes the stacksize of the supplied icon.
You should pass the new stacksize in bytes to this option.


@{u}Example:@{uu} "DoIcon sys:yourtool newss=8192"
         Yeah... now yourtool has a stacksize of 8192 bytes... :)

@endnode

@node copyStacksize
@prev Usage

COPYSTACKSIZE

minimum acceptable abbreviation: "COPYSS"

This option can only be used together with the @{" TO-Option " Link DestinationFile}!

The value of the stacksize is copied from a source into a destination icon.


@{u}Example:@{uu} "DoIcon source_icon to dest_icon copyss"

@endnode

@node Defaulttool
@prev Usage

DEFAULTTOOL

minimum acceptable abbreviation: "DT"

This switch displays the Defaulttool of the supplied icon.
The icon should be of type DISK or PROJECT.
But ALL icon-types are checked, because even a TOOL-icon can have
a defaulttool! The Tool does not use it, but there may be one
stored in the iconfile!


@{u}Example:@{uu} "DoIcon sys:disk dt" should return "SYS:System/DiskCopy"

@endnode

@node newDefaulttool
@prev Usage

NEWDEFAULTTOOL

minimum acceptable abbreviation: "NEWDT"

This option changes the defaulttool of the supplied icon.
The icon should be of type DISK or PROJECT.
You can pass any string to this option, but if there are spaces in
the string you must embrace it with quotation-marks.

If you want search for a specific defaulttool and replace it with a
new one you can use this option together with @{"searchDefaulttool" Link searchDefaulttool}.


@{u}Example:@{uu} "DoIcon sys:disk newdt=SYS:myDiskCopy"
         
@endnode

@node copyDefaulttool
@prev Usage

COPYDEFAULTTOOL

minimum acceptable abbreviation: "COPYDT"

This option can only be used together with the @{" TO-Option " Link DestinationFile}!

The value of the defaulttool is copied from a source into a destination icon.


@{u}Example:@{uu} "DoIcon source_icon to dest_icon copydt"
         
@endnode

@node searchDefaulttool
@prev Usage

SEARCHDEFAULTTOOL

minimum acceptable abbreviation: "SEARCHDT"

This option is used for searching a specific defaulttool and replacing it
with a new one. The new defaulttool must be supplied via the @{"newDefaulttool" Link newDefaulttool}
option.

As a search argument you can use either the complete name of the defaulttool
or simply a pattern.


@{u}Examples:@{uu} "DoIcon sys:#? searchdt=c:less newdt=c:muchmore deep"
          This checks every icon on your system-partition and replaces
          any occurance of "c:less" with "c:muchmore".

          "DoIcon sys:#? searchdt=#?less newdt=c:muchmore deep"
          This checks all icons and replaces any defaulttool that ends 
          with "less" with "c:muchmore".


@endnode


@node Depth
@prev Usage

DEPTH

minimum acceptable abbreviation: "D"

This switch displays the number of bit-planes of the supplied icon.
Icon-images normaly consist of 1, 2, 3, 4 or 8 bit-planes.
This refers to 2, 4, 8, 16 or 256 colors.

@endnode

@node stripDepth
@prev Usage

STRIPDEPTH

minimum acceptable abbreviation: "STRIPD"

This option strips an icon down to a specified number of bit-planes.
You can use 1, 2, 3, or 4 bit-planes.


@{u}Example:@{uu} "DoIcon sys:disk stripd=2"
         This strips your icon down to 2 bit-planes (4 colors), provided
         that the original icon consisted of 3 or more bit-planes.

@endnode

@node DepthTo8
@prev Usage

DEPTHTO8

This switch converts an 3 bit-plane icon to an 8 bit-plane icon.
On a Workbench with more than 8 colors some icons with 3 bit-planes
are not displayed correctly, but with "DepthTo8" you can convert these icons.

After conversion the icon should be displayed correctly.


@endnode

@node Remap
@prev Usage

REMAP

This switch exchanges color 1 and 2 of the icon.

WB 1.x uses as standard color scheme "orange/white/black/blue", but
with WB2.0+ the scheme changed to "grey/black/white/blue and old
icons appeared weird with this new color scheme.

So you can use the Remap-switch on these icons and make them look normal.

@endnode

@node RemapMWB
@prev Usage

REMAPMWB

This option is usefull for people that use a 4 color Workbench and are
tired of all this MagicWB icons, that look so bad with 4 colors!
If you use this option on a MagicWB icon the colors are remapped in a way
that the icon looks even with 4 colors nice and it is stripped down to 
2 bit-planes (4 colors).
Two remap-methods are supported. Method 1 looks always acceptable, but
method 2 looks maybe better in some cases. 


@{u}Example:@{uu} "DoIcon sys:sampleicon remapmwb=1"  (remap-method 1)
         "DoIcon sys:othericon remapmwb=2"   (remap-method 2)

@endnode



@node Highlight
@prev Usage

HIGHLIGHT

minimum acceptable abbreviation: "HL"

This switch displays the highlight-method of the supplied icon.
This can be IMAGE, COMPLEMENT or BACKFILL.


@{u}Example:@{uu} "DoIcon sys:disk hl" may return IMAGE

@endnode

@node newHighlight
@prev Usage

NEWHIGHLIGHT

minimum acceptable abbreviation: "NEWHL"

This option changes the highlightmethod of the supplied icon.
It needs one of the following strings as input:
IMAGE, COMPLEMENT, BACKFILL.


@{u}Example:@{uu} "DoIcon sys:disk newhl=backfill"
         This will change the disk-icon to BACKFILL-mode.
         
@endnode

@node copyImage
@prev Usage

COPYIMAGE

minimum acceptable abbreviation: "COPYIMG"

This option can only be used together with the @{" TO-Option " Link DestinationFile}!

The icon image is copied from a source to a destination icon.


@{u}Example:@{uu} "DoIcon source_icon to dest_icon copyimage"
         
@endnode

@node swapImage
@prev Usage

SWAPIMAGE

minimum acceptable abbreviation: "SIMG"


With this switch the icon images (normal-/select-image) are swapped.


@{u}Example:@{uu} "DoIcon youricon swapimage"
         
@endnode

@node Tooltypes
@prev Usage

TOOLTYPES

minimum acceptable abbreviation: "TT"

This switch displays all tooltypes found in the iconfile.

@endnode

@node changeTooltype
@prev Usage

CHANGETOOLTYPE + NUM

minimum acceptable abbreviation: "CTT"

With this option you can change an existing tooltype to a new one.
Simply pass the new tooltype to the option and the number of the
old tooltype as an additional option.
If there are any spaces or a "=" in the new tooltype string you must 
embrace it in quotation-marks.

If you want search for a specific tooltype and replace it with a new one,
you can use this option together with @{"searchTooltypes" Link searchTooltypes}.


@{u}Examples:@{uu} "DoIcon sys:yourtool ctt=DONOTWAIT num=1"
           This will change the tooltype at position 1 to "DONOTWAIT".

          "DoIcon sys:yourtool ctt="STARTPRI=5" num=2"
           This will change the tooltype at position 2 to "STARTPRI=5".

@endnode

@node addTooltype
@prev Usage

ADDTOOLTYPE

minimum acceptable abbreviation: "ATT"

With this option you can add a tooltype to the tooltype-list of the icon.
Simply pass the new tooltype to the option.
If there are any spaces or a "=" in the new tooltype string you must 
embrace it in quotation-marks.


@{u}Example:@{uu} "DoIcon sys:yourtool att=DONOTWAIT"
          This will append "DONOTWAIT" to the tooltype-list of "yourtool".

@endnode

@node copyTooltypes
@prev Usage

COPYTOOLTYPE

minimum acceptable abbreviation: "COPYTT"

This option can only be used together with the @{" TO-Option " Link DestinationFile}!

@{b}New for version 1.6:@{ub} The option has been renamed from COPYTOOLTYPES/S to
COPYTOOLTYPE/N. If you supply a "0" as argument, the complete tooltype array is
copied from a source to a destination icon (as in previous DoIcon versions).
With version 1.6 you can copy a specific tooltype from a source to a destination
icon by given the position-number.


@{u}Example:@{uu} "DoIcon source_icon to dest_icon copytt=0"
          This copies the complete tooltype array.

         "DoIcon source_icon to dest_icon copytt=2"
          This copies the second entry of the tooltype array.

@endnode

@node updateTooltypes
@prev Usage

UPDATETOOLTYPES

minimum acceptable abbreviation: "UPTT"

This option can only be used together with the @{" TO-Option " Link DestinationFile}!

Since version 1.6 you can use this option together with @{" searchTooltypes " Link searchTooltypes}.


The tooltype array from the souce icon is compared with the tooltype array of
the destination icon. Every tooltype that is in the source icon, but not in the
destination icon is added to it.

Sometimes this option is usefull if you got a new version of a program and want
to copy it over the old program. Maybe some there are new tooltypes in the new
version, but if you copy it over your old icon you loose your custom tooltype
settings.
With "updateTooltypes" you can manage this little problem, because only new
tooltypes are copied and the values of the old tooltypes stay untouched.


@{u}Example:@{uu} "DoIcon source_icon to dest_icon uptt"


   With these given tooltype arrays the result would look like this:


   source_icon          dest_icon (before)          dest_icon (after)

   (DONOTWAIT)          DONOTWAIT                   DONOTWAIT    
   CX_POPKEY=F1         CX_POPKEY=F9                CX_POPKEY=F9
   (CX_PRIORITY=-1)     CX_PRIORITY=-1              CX_PRIORITY=-1
   (PORTNAME=ABC)                                   (PORTNAME=ABC)
   FASTMODE                                         FASTMODE
                        STARTPRI=-20                STARTPRI=-20
   FOOBAR               (FOOBAR)                    (FOOBAR)


@endnode

@node toggleTooltype
@prev Usage

TOGGLETOOLTYPE

minimum acceptable abbreviation: "TTT"

With this option you can toggle a tooltype on or off.
You should pass the number of the tooltype to the option.
If the specified tooltype is enabled it's turned off and
if it's disabled it's turned on.


@{u}Example:@{uu} "Doicon sys:yourtool ttt=1" will toggle tooltype number one.

@endnode

@node deleteTooltype
@prev Usage

DELETETOOLTYPE

minimum acceptable abbreviation: "DELTT"

With this option you can delete the given tooltype.
You must pass the number of the tooltype to the option.

If you want search for a specific tooltype and delete it from the
tooltype-list, then you can use this option together with @{"searchTooltypes" Link searchTooltypes}.


@{u}Example:@{uu} "DoIcon sys:yourtool deltt=5" will delete tooltype number five.


@endnode

@node clearTooltypes
@prev Usage

CLEARTOOLTYPES

minimum acceptable abbreviation: "CLEARTT"

This switch clears the complete tooltype array of the supplied icon!
Yes, ALL tooltypes are deleted!

@endnode

@node sortTooltypes
@prev Usage

SORTTOOLTYPES

minimum acceptable abbreviation: "SORTTT"

This switch sorts the complete tooltype array of the supplied icon!

@endnode

@node searchTooltypes
@prev Usage

SEARCHTOOLTYPES

minimum acceptable abbreviation: "SEARCHTT"

With this option you can search for a specific tooltype and either replace it
with a new one (supplied via @{"changeTooltype" Link changeTooltype}), delete it
with @{"deleteTooltype" Link deleteTooltype} or copy/update it to a destination icon
with the @{"TO option" Link DestinationFile}.

@{b}New for version 1.6:@{ub} If a destination icon is given, the new tooltype or
all matching tooltypes of the source icon is/are copied to the destination icon.
If a destination icon is given and also the @{"updatetooltypes-switch" Link updateTooltypes} is set
the new tooltype or all matching tooltypes is/are only copied to the destination
icon if they are not already in there.
(see examples below)

If you use "deleteTooltype" (deltt) without the search-function you have 
to supply the number of the tooltype to delete, but together with the 
search-function "deltt" is used like a switch. This means, you have to
supply any number, but this number is not used within DoIcon.
(So simply type something like "deltt=1" if you supplied a tooltype via
 the "searchTooltypes" argument.)

As a search argument you can use either the complete name of the tooltype
or simply a pattern.


@{u}Examples:@{uu} "DoIcon sys:yourtool searchtt=donotwait deltt=1"
           This deletes the tooltype "donotwait" in the icon "yourtool".

          "DoIcon sys:#? searchtt=(#?) deltt=1 deep"
           This scans all icons on your system-partition and deletes 
           all disabled tooltypes!

          "DoIcon sys:wbstartup/#? searchtt=cx_popup#? ctt="cx_popup=no" "
           This scans all icons in your wbstartup-drawer and replaces all
           tooltypes beginning with "cx_popup" with "cx_popup=no".

          "DoIcon icon1 to icon2 searchtt=cx#?"
           This copies all tooltypes beginning with "cx" from icon1 to icon2.

          "DoIcon icon1 to icon2 searchtt=cx#? updatetooltypes"
           This copies all tooltypes beginning with "cx" from icon1 to icon2
           if they are not already found in icon2.

@endnode

@node checkTooltypeValue
@prev Usage

CHECKTOOLTYPEVALUE

minimum acceptable abbreviation: "CTTV"

With this option you can check icons for a specific tooltype-name.
If DoIcon finds the given tooltype-name in the checked icon, the value
of this tooltype is returned.
You must supply the complete tooltype-name to this option!


@{u}Example:@{uu} "DoIcon sys:wbstartup/#? cttv=startpri"
          This checks the icons in your wbstartup-drawer for the 
          tooltype "startpri" and outputs its value, if it is found
          in the tooltype list.           

@endnode 

@node stripNewIcon
@prev Usage

STRIPNEWICON

minimum acceptable abbreviation: "STRIPNI"

With this switch you can remove all 'NewIcon' entries from the tooltype
array.
(This switch is for people who don't use NewIcons and want to get rid
 of the NewIcon tooltypes.)

@endnode

@node WBInfo
@prev Usage

WBINFO

acceptable alias: "GUI"

With this switch you can call the Workbench information-requester.

@{b}OS 3.x is needed for this operation! @{ub}


@{u}Example:@{uu} "DoIcon sys:yourtool wbinfo"
 
@endnode

@node ImageToSource
@prev Usage

IMAGETOSOURCE

minimum acceptable abbreviation: "IMGTOSRC"

With this switch you can create C-sourcecode from a given icon image.
DoIcon outputs a complete image-struct (LeftEdge, TopEdge, Width, Height, 
Depth, ImageData, PlanePick, PlaneOnOff, NextImage) for the gadget-image
and the select-image (if necessary).
The sourcecode is written to "RAM:IconImageData.c".

This option may only be usefull for programers... :-)

@endnode

@node Delete
@prev Usage

DELETE

If one delete an icon with the AmigaDOS "Delete" command the icon does
not disappear from the Workbench (if it's currently displayed).

If you use the Delete-switch, the Workbench is updated automatically
(the icon disappears immediatly).


@{u}Example:@{uu} "DoIcon sys:yourdir/#? delete deep"
          This deletes all icons in "yourdir", including all sub-directories.


@{u}Restrictions:@{uu} The Delete-funktion does not work on DISK-icons.
              The iconfile is deleted, but the icon does not disappear
              from the Workbench.

@endnode

@node KillOldInfo
@prev Usage

KILLOLDINFO

With this switch set, DoIcon recursivly scans the supplied directory
or device and deletes all ".info" files.
This files are used under Kickstart/Workbench 1.x only, they are useless
on 2.0+ systems.
To get rid of them and to save some disk-space "KillOldInfo" can be used.
With CTRL-C you can abort the scan.


@{u}Examples:@{uu} "DoIcon sys: killoldinfo" scans your whole system-partition.

          "DoIcon yourdir killoldinfo" 
           scans the directory "yourdir" and all it's subdirectories and
           deletes all ".info"-files.

@endnode

@node Deep
@prev Usage

DEEP

acceptable alias: "ALL"

This switch can be used if you supply a pattern to the @{"File-argument" Link File}.
If the switch is set DoIcon enters all sub-directories it finds and scans for 
icons matching the given pattern.

(Examples can be found in the explanation of the @{"File-argument" Link File}.)

@endnode

@node Quiet
@prev Usage

QUIET

This switch forces DoIcon to suppress all text-output.
This is mainly usefull if you are workings with patterns and don't want
DoIcon to comment every operation.

@endnode

@node Locale

@{u}Localization@{uu}

DoIcon provides full locale support when used with Workbench 2.1 or higher.

Currently supported languages:

   · English (builtin)
   · Deutsch
   · Suomi
   · Français 
   · Dansk
   · Polski
   · Svenska
   · Italiano


Included guides:

   · English
   · Deutsch
   · Italiano


If your language is not supported, you can translate the provided
"DoIcon.ct" file and send it back to me.
I will compile it and include it into the next release of DoIcon.
Translation is very easy, just fill in your translations above
the original english texts in the DoIcon.ct file.

If you use accents or umlauts please uuencode your email, because
these characters don't survive 7-Bit transmissions!

Please see @{" Author's Address " Link Address} on how to reach me.
 
@endnode

